<br>
I'm a pacifist. I abhore, loathe, detest ... get your thesaurus and pick a word, I'll feel it ... towards violence. I'd be scared witless if I were drafted, but I'd go. What do you have to gain by abandoning your country? Do you live here? Do you like it here? I'd hate being drafted, I'd be reluctant to go, but I would. Call it honor, call it duty, any name you want to give it, it all boils down to one thing: illusions. You think you can live free like this and not pay a price for it? Hop in a time machine and go back to being five yours old when you didn't need to worry about this. Thera ARE comforts to being drafted, there's very little chance, if you're drafted, you'll be SENT to war. To my understanding, if this is a war, it'll be a short one. If you're drafted, you'll be there to help in times of need ... you wouldn't normally help someone in need? If not, then it speaks volumes of who you really are, if you do, the only difference is that you'll be in a uniform doing it this time. Suck it up. Close your eyes, clench your fists, cry if you have to, but face the reality of the situation. Yes, you're scared ... but you're not alone. Which would you rather be more afraid of, dieing or dieing without having lifted a finger to do something about it?<br>
