<br>
I've always wondered however, if I could look a man in the eyes and kill him. Even if he came running at me, with a weapon in hand. I know my first thought would be defending myself, but would I be able to cock a gun, blow his brains out, pump bullets into a chest with sprays of blood and gore? Watch the light in his eyes fade? Even if I knew this one death might save hundreds more. Could I live with myself?<br>
<br>
I suppose people find a way to do it. I suppose I would too.<br>
<br>
I grew up on a farm as a kid. I remember being 14 and at my friend's house after riding horses all day. Her parents were in town for the day. Her dog got hit my a car - it nearly ripped the animal in two. We found it screaming in front of her house near the road. It made such a horrible noise. We had to shoot it and put it out of its pain. She couldn't do it. She tried, but couldn't. I had to. I vomited after.<br>
<br>
So back to the draft and fear and the whole ball of wax.<br>
<br>
Anyone who goes to war has my admiration that they can do it at all. And my pity. It's a hard, terrible thing. Noble, and a heavy burden.<br>
<br>
I wouldn't judge anyone that's truthful enough to admit they're afraid of being drafted. I know I would be. Wouldn't you?  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFF8DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub18.ezboard.com/ugarlaen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Garlaen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>MithMarr Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#006400>(9/17/01 9:56:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub18.ezboard.com/fmithanielmarrdailynewsfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=823.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   &gt; I don't want to get drafted!</span><hr size=1> I was a reservist during Iraq.  My unit was on alert, but was never activated to go over.  I wouldn't have liked it, but I was glad to serve my country in whatever aspect it needed.  <br>
<br>
I can understand people's concerns over being drafted, but I also feel that we, as a nation, have lost that aspect of our culture that looks positively on the notion of serving the nation in return for the freedoms it grants.  When I joined up, my grandfather called me and shared several experiences he had during his time in Korea (he lost his brother and best friend there).  At the same time, he never complained about being drafted.  He was called and he served.  It's what you did back then.  <br>
<br>
I guess I got my desire to give back from him.  Sure, it was the reserves and I wasn't out there every day like so many others do, but reserve and national guard units are vital to the armed forces, as well.<br>
<br>
For those people who feel that this will be a short military action or won't involve ground troups, I disagree.  Guerilla warfare and terrorist tactics are built around the concept of small units fighting larger, organized operations.  We trained Bin Laden in this and he has perfected it.  The Taliban has provided a sanctuary for these people.  The people of Afghanistan do not necessarily support the Taliban, but what choices do they have?  When we leave, they will still be living there.  <br>
<br>
Bin Laden and the rest will go underground in the mountains and caves requiring us to send in troops to root them out.  Air strikes against targets will occur, but more to just break up the infrastructure.  We need to work with the financial institutions and local government to seize Bin Laden's assets, continue to gain political support from the surrounding nations and remove the Taliban, Bin Laden and all of their followers from the region.  When new leaders rise to take their places, we need to remove them.  <br>
<br>
All of this will not be done in a few weeks.  We are talking a long-term military commitment.  Prior to this, I really did not support the US involvement in the Middle East.  Our only real interest there was oil.  Now, it is national security and a responsibility to the world.  We trained Bin Laden and introduced him to his network of terrorist.  We help establish the Taliban during the Soviet/Afghan battles.  Now we have to clean up the mess that has resulted.  It's our obligation to the world and our children.<br>
